# Amazon EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)

Amazon EC2 is part of the **Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)** offerings from AWS. It allows you to rent virtual machines and provides resizable compute capacity in the cloud.

---

## Key Capabilities

- **Renting virtual machines (EC2)**
- **Storing data on virtual drives (EBS)**
- **Distributing load across machines (ELB)**
- **Auto-scaling services using ASG (Auto Scaling Groups)**

---

## EC2 Sizing & Configuration Options

- **Operating System (OS)**: Linux, Windows, macOS
- **Compute Power**: CPU cores and speed
- **Memory (RAM)**: Allocate based on workload
- **Storage Options**:
  - Network-attached (EBS, EFS)
  - Instance store (hardware-based)
- **Networking**: Network card speed, public IP support
- **Security**: Security Groups (firewall rules)
- **EC2 User Data**: Bootstrap scripts to run at first launch

---

## EC2 User Data & Bootstrapping

User Data is a script (typically Bash or PowerShell) that runs at the first boot of an EC2 instance.

### Use Cases:
- Install software (NGINX, MySQL, Node.js)
- Update packages
- Configure environment files
- Start services
- Pull code from Git or S3

### Example Script:

```bash
#!/bin/bash
yum update -y
yum install -y httpd
systemctl start httpd
systemctl enable httpd
echo "Deployed via bootstrap" > /var/www/html/index.html
